{<<...I could not have lived without chess; on walks and even in my sleep I
was pursued by the pieces, and in my head a genuine battle took place...The
game of chess is the ideal aim of my life!>> wrote Pillsbury in his
autobiography. The great American player Harry Nelson Pillsbury is an unusual
exception among the majority of his famous colleagues. Not only was he no
child prodigy, but until the age of 16 he altogheter knew nothing of chess.
But within just five years, in the mid 1890s, Pillsbury was already one of the
top masters, and was successfully competing even with World Champions.
Pillsbury also became renowned for his phenomenal ability at blindfold chess -
he could simultaneously battle against more then twenty opponents. Pillsbury
also introduced much into chess theory. It is sufficient to recall his famous
counter-attack in the Queen's Gambit (usually known as the Cambridge-Springs
Defence - n.T.) and his very powerful attacking set-up in another variation of
the same opening. Even today his ideas are used at the very highest level (for
example, in the 1983 Candidates 1/4 Final match Kasparov-Belyavsky). For this
reason the opinion of the chess historian Ludwig Bachmann constitutes a
misconception:<< ...Pillsbury did not open any new paths in chess, did not
become a teacher and was not a creator.>>  On the contrary, many prominent
players of an active positional style, born in 20th century, are to a greater
or lesser extent his pupils.  In the present game there was not a tense
struggle. The position of White, who was the first chess king, collapsed of
its own accord...} 1. e4 e5 2. f4 Bc5 3. Nf3 d6 4. Bc4 Nc6 5. c3 {The opening
is an unusual hybrid of the King's Gambit and Italian Game. This experiment
does not succeed, but to refute it the inspired and amazingly vigorous play of
the young Pillsbury was required. An amusing fact is that White's last move in
this given position has not found its way into modern opening guides...  5...}
