{In this game J.H.White, one of the authors of "Modern Chess Opening", plays
the newly invented Budapest Gambit. Both players go all out to win, and a fine
struggle follows Capablanca's loss - or sacrifice - of the queen.} 1. d4 Nf6 2.
c4 e5 3. dxe5 Ng4 4. Nf3 {Capablanca goes his own way, avoiding book lines in
so far as they existed. 4...} 4... Bc5 5. e3 Nc6 6. Bd2 O-O 7. Bc3 Re8 8. Be2
d6 {Very enterprising.} (8... Ngxe5 9. Nxe5 Nxe5 10. O-O {
would not be altogheter satisfactory dor Black; if for instance 10...} 10... d6
11. b4 $1) 9. exd6 Bxe3 $1 10. fxe3 {Capablanca was not one to refuse a
challenge. He could castle instead, with a defensible game but not much more.
10...} 10... Nxe3 11. Qd2 $1 Nxc4 12. Qg5 f6 $1 13. Qd5+ Be6 14. Qd3 Nxd6 15.
O-O $1 ({If} 15. Nbd2 Bf5 $1 {
Instead White gives up his queen in order to stem the attack.}) 15... Bc4 16.
Qxc4+ Nxc4 17. Bxc4+ Kh8 18. Nbd2 Qd6 {Black has a small material advantage,
but his game is not easy because he will be much harassed by White's extra
pieces.} 19. Kh1 Rad8 20. Rae1 Qc5 21. Rxe8+ Rxe8 22. a3 b5 {Black correctly
advances his pawn majority. It would be absurd, for instance, to attempt a
king's side attack against White's many pieces.} 23. Ba2 a5 24. Nb3 Qc4 25.
Nfd2 Qe2 26. Nc1 Qe3 27. Nf3 Rd8 28. Re1 Qc5 29. Nb3 Qb6 30. Nbd4 Nxd4 31. Bxd4
c5 32. Bg1 Qc6 33. h4 h5 {White makes room for his king, and Black does the
same. This was the kind of chance that White was waiting for, because he now
has chances of a king's side attack. Fron his point fo view the disparity of
four pieces against two is at an optimum: had he not excanged some pieces the
ratio would have been favourable, whilst if he were now to exchange rooks he
would hardly have a sufficient attacking force.} ({Burn reccommended} 33... a4
{with the idea of creating a tangible threat on the queen's side.}) 34. Bf7 f5
{Black sets a trap but opens more pockets for White's pieces.} ({
Afterwards Black suggested} 34... Qc7 {
simply giving up the KRP. The chances would be about even.}) 35. Ng5 Qc7 36.
Bxh5 Qg3 37. Nf3 Qd6 $2 {At the critical point of the game Black changes plan.}
({He intended} 37... g6 38. Bh2 ({or perhaps} 38. Re5 {
with the idea of mopping up some pawns for his piece.}) 38... Qxe1+ 39. Nxe1
gxh5 {but apparently fears the endgame after} 40. Be5+ Kg8 41. Nf3 {In fact, it
would be drawn. If, however, Black withdraws his queen in the hope of winning
then he misjudges the position.}) 38. Ne5 Qf6 39. g3 Rd2 {Now Black's only
advantage, the queen's side pawn majority, disappears; and White winds up with
a slendid finish, the minor pieces crowding out the queen:} 40. Bxc5 Rc2 41.
Bd4 Qa6 42. Nf7+ Kh7 43. Ng5+ Kh6 44. Bf3 Qc8 45. Re6+ g6 46. Re7 Rc1+ 47. Kh2
Rc2+ 48. Kh3 f4+ 49. g4 Qg8 50. Nf7+ Kh7 51. Ne5+ {When we see a game of this
quality, against a high-ranking national player, we have to rub our eyes and
to remember that it was played simultaneously alongside twenty-seven other
games. Capablanca is reported to have played 240 moves in the first half-hour,
and in the later stages of this game Black had some difficulty contending
against Capablanca's fantastic speed of play.} 1-0

