{Opening? I don't know whether to call it a Q-Indian or K-indian.} 1. Nf3 Nf6
2. c4 b6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. Nc3 Bb7 7. d4 Ne4 8. Nxe4 Bxe4 9. d5
{Nimzowitsch's forgotten idea for conducting this opening was revived by
Portisch (as Black) in his game with Andersson from Palma 1971.} ({
In this later game White preferred} 9. Be3 {
which led to his advantage after 9...} 9... d5 $5 10. Rc1 dxc4 11. Rxc4 c5 12.
Rc1) 9... e5 $1 10. Be3 f5 11. Ne1 Bxg2 12. Nxg2 d6 {An interesting position.
Black's normal strategy would be to storm forwards on the King side with his
mobile pawns, but the fact that White's KP is on e2 rather then e4 makes it
more difficult for Black to fix on a target. White's normal plan would be to
launch a Queen side advance with b2-b4, c4-c5 etc. breaking into Black's camp
at the sensitive point c7. However, the absence of White's KP from e4 also
exerts an influence over White's plan of campaign in that (after c4-c5) is QP
will be deprived of much of his support. In such strategically complex
position Numzowitsch excelled. Now many of his original ideas have been
absorbed into master tecnique or incorporated into "openings theory".} 13. Qd2
Nd7 14. f3 $1 {A useful consolidating move directed against the mobility of
Black's KP and KBP. 14...} 14... a5 15. Rab1 Nc5 {Provocation. Also possible
was the more solipstic procedure Rf7,Qf8 followed by h7-h6 and g6-g5. But
Nimzowitsch prefers to encourage activity from his opponent since he correctly
perceives that this very activity will ultimately be White's undoing.} 16. b3
Rf7 $1 {And prophylaxis! Observe the way in which Nimzowitsch guards the c7
point before it is attacked.} 17. a3 Qf8 18. Rfc1 h5 {A device for gaining
space on the King side which is now regulation in the King's Indian Defence.
Given time Black will also play g6-g5 with an awesome array of pawns.} 19. b4
axb4 20. axb4 Nd7 21. c5 {This temporary sacrifice of a pawn looks most
promising since it exposes a number of weaknesses in the Black position.
However, with this move White is walking straight into a combinative ambush;
it could be said that he started out on the ambush trail when he was lured
into a Queen side advance (with gain of tempo) by 15...Nc5, but what other
choice did White have? Black holds the initiative on the King wing so the only
alternative to Queen side activity would be passive defence. Attractive though
its execution might appear Nimzowitsch had prepared so efficiently for the
possibility of a White Queen side advance that the whole plan of carrying it
through could be classed as a collective error.} ({If} 21. Ra1 {
to seize the QR file, then 21...} 21... e4 $1 22. Bd4 exf3 23. exf3 Ne5 {
with manifold threats.}) 21... dxc5 22. bxc5 Nxc5 23. Bxc5 bxc5 {
White has had to weaken his dark squares in order to shatter Black's pawns.}
24. Rb5 {"White seems to be in the ascendant but Black has not been marking
time. In fact he has been engaged in the accumulation of attacking energy (QR
file, h6-d2 diagonal, mobile pawn mass, etc.) and now emerges with a series of
noxious blows which had completely escaped White's attention. We might add, by
the way, that without Black's cooperation (the partly superfluous and partly
provocatory Nc5) White would scarcely ever have been able to arrange his
break-through with pawn-c5. (Nimzowitsch)} 24... Bh6 25. f4 exf4 26. gxf4 $2 (
26. Nxf4 $1 c4 27. Qd4 Qa3 28. Qxc4 Bxf4 29. gxf4 {and White has drawing
chances in spite of the exposed position of the King. Presumably White
retained his Knigt as a comfort for his King, but the Knight dies anyway, and
the White KBP expires in sympathy, thus leaving the King virtually devoid of
support for his dotage.}) 26... c4 $1 {The ambush is spung and events now
develop by force. This counter-sacrifice has the effect of galvanising Black's
entire army which had hitherto slumbered peacefully within the confines of the
back two ranks.} 27. Rxc4 Ra1+ 28. Rc1 Qa3 29. Rbb1 ({After} 29. Rxa1 Qxa1+ {
Black's advantage is manifest: more secure King, Bishop for Knight in an open
position and better pawns (two pawn islands to three).}) 29... Ra2 30. Rc2 (30.
Qe1 Qe7 31. e3 g5 $1 32. Ra1 (32. fxg5 Qxg5 33. Qg3 Rg7 $19) 32... Rxa1 33.
Rxa1 gxf4 34. exf4 Qc5+ {followed by Qxc5 with a good extra pawn. (Nimzowitsch)
}) 30... Rxc2 31. Qxc2 Bxf4 {The final point of the cpmbination. Black wins a
pawn and bares the white King. It was also possible to play 31...Bf8,
retaining the Bishop for attacking purposes, when White could hardly resist
successfully, so disorganised are his lines of defence (backward KP, straying
QP, exposed KBP and unsheltered K).} 32. Nxf4 Qe3+ 33. Kg2 Qxf4 {An extra pawn
plus the more secure position should amount to a verdict of -+, but...} 34.
Rb8+ Kh7 35. Qc3 Rg7 36. Re8 h4 37. Qf3 Qd4 $2 (37... Qxf3+ $1 {
followed by Rd7 and Kh6 would have won. Now the win slips away.}) 38. e4 $1 {
Nimzowitsch admitted quite frankly in his notes that he had forgotten that
this move was legal! White's counter-attack against Black's KBP and KRP forces
Nimzowitsch to start all over again. 38...} 38... Qa4 39. Re6 Rf7 40. Kh3 Qc2
41. Qf4 Qc3+ 42. Kxh4 Qg7 43. Kg3 g5 44. Qe5 f4+ 45. Kf2 Qxe5 46. Rxe5 Kg6 {
Can Black win this position? The disappoinment of not having won already, plus
the fact that this position is a dead draw (after 47.h2-h3) might have caused
many masters to abandon the struggle and sue for peace, but there is one
possibility left.} 47. Kf3 $2 {Jeopardising his game once again. 47...} 47...
g4+ $1 {The final shot in Black's arsenal.} 48. Kg2 (48. Kxg4 f3 $19) 48... Rf8
49. Re7 ({The last chance was} 49. Re6+ Kg5 50. Re5+ {
and 51.Re7 with some hope left. The text loses.}) 49... f3+ 50. Kf2 Rh8 51. Kg1
Ra8 52. Rxc7 Ra1+ 53. Kf2 Ra2+ 54. Kg1 Rg2+ 55. Kh1 Rd2 56. Kg1 Rd1+ 57. Kf2
Rh1 58. d6 ({Or} 58. Kg3 Rg1+ 59. Kf2 Rg2+ {and wins.}) 58... Rxh2+ {
And Black's passed pawns are the more powerful.} 59. Ke3 Re2+ {
To cut off White's King.} 60. Kd3 Re1 61. Rc2 ({Black wins also after} 61. d7
f2 62. d8=Q f1=Q+ 63. Kc2 Rc1+ 64. Kb2 Rb1+ 65. Ka2 Ra1+ 66. Kb2 Qb1+ 67. Kc3
Qc1+ 68. Kb3 Ra3+ 69. Kb4 Qb2+ 70. Kc4 Rc3+) 61... Kf7 (61... Kf7 {After} 62.
Rf2 Ke6 {White is completely helpless. An eventful game.}) 0-1

